 {"id":"beads_rust-c0v","title":"EPIC: Agent Ergonomics & Dual-Mode CLI","description":"# Agent Ergonomics & Dual-Mode CLI

## Background & Rationale

Based on research of mature CLI tools (beads_viewer, cass, xf) and 2025-2026 best practices for AI coding agent integration, br needs a dual-mode CLI architecture that serves both human developers (interactive mode) and AI coding agents (structured output mode).

### Why This Matters
- ~85% of developers now use AI tools for coding (2025 data)
- AI agents like Claude Code need deterministic, structured JSON output
- Same binary should serve both humans and agents - single source of truth
- Current br outputs are human-friendly but not agent-optimized

## Goals
Implement `--robot-*` flags and structured output modes that enable AI coding agents to programmatically interact with br, parse results, and make intelligent decisions based on issue data.

## In-Scope
- `--robot-help` - Machine-readable help (JSON schema of commands/flags)
- `--robot-triage` - Ranked actionable items with scores and reasons
- `--robot-next` - Single top priority item with claim command
- `--robot-plan` - Execution tracks showing parallelizable work
- `--robot-graph` - Dependency DAG as JSON/DOT/Mermaid
- `--robot-priority` - Priority misalignment detection
- Structured JSON error output with codes, hints, retryable flags
- TTY detection for automatic mode switching
- `NO_COLOR` environment variable support

## Out-of-Scope (v1)
- Full TUI mode (separate epic)
- MCP server integration (separate epic)

## Acceptance Criteria
- All `--robot-*` flags implemented and documented
- JSON output is deterministic and stable across runs
- Error output includes structured metadata
- Agent workflows (ready → claim → work → close) are streamlined
- Documentation includes agent integration guide

## Technical Approach

### Structured Error Output
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "ISSUE_NOT_FOUND",
    "message": "Issue bd-xyz123 not found",
    "hint": "Did you mean bd-xyz12? Use 'br list' to see all issues",
    "retryable": false
  }
}
```

### Robot Mode Detection
- Explicit `--robot-*` flags take precedence
- `--json` implies structured output
- Check `isatty(stdout)` for auto-detection
- Respect `NO_COLOR` and `TERM=dumb`

## References
- Anthropic: Claude Code Best Practices for Agentic Coding
- beads_viewer: `--robot-triage`, `--robot-plan` implementation
- cass: `--robot-help` pattern
- Charm ecosystem: gum, lipgloss for styling

## Dependencies
- Phase 3: Relations & Search (for graph analysis)
- Colored Terminal Output (for human mode contrast)","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"epic","estimated_minutes":0,"created_at":"2026-01-16T18:47:49.786338482Z","created_by":"Dicklesworthstone","updated_at":"2026-01-16T18:54:35.306550245Z","closed_at":"2026-01-16T18:54:35.306550245Z","close_reason":"ERROR: --robot-* flags are bv's domain, not br's. br is non-invasive CLI only. See AGENTS.md 'Using bv as an AI Sidecar' section."}
 {"id":"beads_rust-c58","title":"Export Error Policies","description":"## Overview
Implement configurable error handling policies for JSONL export. Different use cases require different trade-offs between strictness and resilience.

## Error Policy Enum
```rust
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Copy, PartialEq, Eq, Default)]
pub enum ExportErrorPolicy {
    /// Abort export on any error (default for sync)
    #[default]
    Strict,

    /// Skip problematic records, export what we can
    BestEffort,

    /// Export valid records, report failures (for debugging)
    Partial,

    /// Only export issues (skip deps/labels/comments on error)
    RequiredCore,
}
```

## Technical Requirements

### Policy Implementation
```rust
pub struct ExportContext {
    pub policy: ExportErrorPolicy,
    pub errors: Vec<ExportError>,
    pub warnings: Vec<String>,
}

impl ExportContext {
    pub fn handle_error(&mut self, err: ExportError) -> Result<(), ExportError> {
        match self.policy {
            ExportErrorPolicy::Strict => {
                // Fail immediately
                Err(err)
            }
            ExportErrorPolicy::BestEffort => {
                // Log and continue
                tracing::warn!("Export error (skipping): {}", err);
                self.errors.push(err);
                Ok(())
            }
            ExportErrorPolicy::Partial => {
                // Record for report, continue
                self.errors.push(err);
                Ok(())
            }
            ExportErrorPolicy::RequiredCore => {
                // Fail only if its a core (issue) error
                match err.entity_type {
                    EntityType::Issue => Err(err),
                    _ => {
                        self.errors.push(err);
                        Ok(())
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Export With Policy
```rust
impl SqliteStorage {
    pub fn export_jsonl_with_policy(
        &self,
        output_dir: &Path,
        policy: ExportErrorPolicy,
    ) -> Result<ExportReport> {
        let mut ctx = ExportContext::new(policy);
        let mut report = ExportReport::new();

        // Export issues
        let issues = self.get_all_issues()?;
        let issues_path = output_dir.join("issues.jsonl");
        let mut issues_file = File::create(&issues_path)?;

        for issue in &issues {
            match serde_json::to_string(issue) {
                Ok(json) => {
                    writeln!(issues_file, "{}", json)?;
                    report.issues_exported += 1;
                }
                Err(e) => {
                    ctx.handle_error(ExportError {
                        entity_type: EntityType::Issue,
                        entity_id: issue.id.clone(),
                        message: e.to_string(),
                    })?;
                }
            }
        }

        // Export dependencies
        let deps = self.get_all_dependencies()?;
        // ... similar pattern

        // Export labels
        let labels = self.get_all_labels()?;
        // ... similar pattern

        // Export comments
        let comments = self.get_all_comments()?;
        // ... similar pattern

        report.errors = ctx.errors;
        report.policy_used = policy;
        Ok(report)
    }
}
```

### CLI Integration
```bash
# Default: strict (fail on any error)
br sync --flush-only

# Best effort: export what we can
br sync --flush-only --error-policy best-effort

# Partial: full report of failures
br sync --flush-only --error-policy partial

# Required core: issues must succeed, others can fail
br sync --flush-only --error-policy required-core
```

### Export Report
```rust
pub struct ExportReport {
    pub issues_exported: usize,
    pub dependencies_exported: usize,
    pub labels_exported: usize,
    pub comments_exported: usize,
    pub errors: Vec<ExportError>,
    pub policy_used: ExportErrorPolicy,
}

pub struct ExportError {
    pub entity_type: EntityType,
    pub entity_id: String,
    pub message: String,
}

impl ExportReport {
    pub fn has_errors(&self) -> bool {
        !self.errors.is_empty()
    }

    pub fn success_rate(&self) -> f64 {
        let total = self.issues_exported + self.dependencies_exported 
                  + self.labels_exported + self.comments_exported;
        let failed = self.errors.len();
        if total + failed == 0 { 1.0 }
        else { total as f64 / (total + failed) as f64 }
    }
}
```

### Output (Human)
```
Export completed with policy: best-effort

Exported:
  156 issues
  234 dependencies (2 errors)
  89 labels
  42 comments (1 error)

Errors (3):
  dependency bd-abc12 -> bd-xyz99: Invalid reference
  dependency bd-def34 -> bd-missing: Target not found
  comment c-123: Serialization failed
```

### Output (JSON)
```json
{
  "policy": "best-effort",
  "exported": {
    "issues": 156,
    "dependencies": 234,
    "labels": 89,
    "comments": 42
  },
  "errors": [
    { "type": "dependency", "id": "bd-abc12", "message": "Invalid reference" }
  ],
  "success_rate": 0.98
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Strict policy fails on first error
- [ ] BestEffort skips errors, continues export
- [ ] Partial exports valid records, reports all failures
- [ ] RequiredCore fails only on issue errors
- [ ] --error-policy CLI flag
- [ ] ExportReport includes error list
- [ ] Human-readable error summary
- [ ] JSON error report

## Unit Tests
- Strict policy aborts on error
- BestEffort continues after error
- Partial collects all errors
- RequiredCore fails on issue error
- RequiredCore succeeds despite dep error
- Error count accurate
- Success rate calculated correctly
- Each entity type triggers correct behavior

## Dependencies
- JSONL Export Implementation
- Model Types
- Error Handling Module

## Rationale
